bib.title: A Study of Nuclear Levels in 32S by the Reaction 28Si(alpha,alpha)28Si and Single Particle Potential Representation

free_txt: Alpha particle beam for 5.5 MeV Van de
Graaff accelerator.
BP
The scattered alpha particles are detected by
silicon surface-barrier detectors. The detectors are
placed in detector collimator housing assemblies.
Alpha particle beam for 5.5 MeV Van de
Graaff accelerator.
In the energy region between 3.8-5.9
MeV 25 resonances were observed. Theoretical fits
were generated with single-, and two-level codes.
Table 1, page 54.
Measurements were made at 82,92,108,118,125,135,155,
165 degrees. The differential cross section is
determined as sigma = (Y cosine theta)/(N n t omega),
where Y is the yield in the number of counts, theta
is the angle between a perpendicular to the target
and the beam direction, N is the number of target
nuclei per cm3, n is the total number of incident
particles, t is target thickness in cm, omega is
solid angle subtended by the detector collimator in
radians.
The mean value of target thickness at 1.698 MeV was
0.989 mg/cm2.  Natural silicon contains 98.92 percent
of 28Si, 0.5 percent of 29Si and 0.58 percent of 30Si.

Quality of vertical scale in Fig. 10a is very poor
and confusing. I had to deduce values using
data from other Figures (x10 factor) in order to keep
data consistent.
The total uncertainty in the differential
cross section was a sum of all the above and equal
6.4%. The way uncertainties can enter into the cross
section is through the fluctuation in yield, the
uncertainty in determining the angle theta, the
ambiguity in the target thickness due to
non-uniformity of the target, and uncertainties in the
total number of particles due to errors in charge
collection, since n is simply the total charge
collected divided by the charge per particle. N, being
the number of nuclei per cm3, is constant, and will
not contribute to any uncertainties. All independent
uncertainties were added in quadratures.
1.8% is statistical fluctuation in yield.
Uncertainty in charge collection was 0.35%.
Uncertainty in the solid angle 0.04%.
Uncertainty in the target thickness 6.4%.
Four detectors were used. They were placed at 82, 118,
135, and 165 degrees which corresponds to 90, 125.3,
140.8, 167.2 degrees in the center of mass system of
28Si + alpha. The differential cross section is
determined as sigma = (Y cosine theta)/(N n t omega),
where Y is the yield in the number of counts, theta
is the angle between a perpendicular to the target
and the beam direction, N is the number of target
nuclei per cm3, n is the total number of incident
particles, t is target thickness in cm, omega is
solid angle subtended by the detector collimator in
radians.
The target was made by evaporating of ~1 mg/cm2 of
natural silicon onto a 25 microg/cm2 thick carbon
backing. The averaged target thickness was 0.990
microg/cm2.  Natural silicon contains 98.92 percent of
28Si, 0.5 percent of 29Si and 0.58 percent of 30Si.
